    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are looking a bit weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kind of yellow, but the top ones look okay for now. any idea what's going on? and how do i fix the soil if i need to?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That yellowing at the bottom is a classic sign of the plants trying to save their energy for the new growth, but it could also be a sign of root rot or nutrient deficiency. To fix the soil, you should test its pH and drainage, as compacted or waterlogged soil is a common cause of these symptoms. If the soil is too wet, you'll need to improve drainage, perhaps by adding more sand or perlite to the mix. If it's too dry or lacks nutrients, you can amend it with compost or a balanced fertilizer. Always check the roots carefully when repotting to ensure they aren't mushy or rotted.",
      "source": "target",
