    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it could be a deficiency right? i read somewhere that nitrogen is usually the culprit when the bottom leaves go yellow first. if it is nitrogen, do i just add more fertilizer or is there something else i should check for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right that nitrogen deficiency often causes the older, lower leaves to yellow first, but it's not the only possibility. Before just adding fertilizer, you should check if the soil is too acidic or if the plants are being shaded out by neighbors. If you do decide to add nitrogen, be careful not to overdo it, as too much fertilizer can actually burn the roots and make the problem worse. It's a good idea to test the soil first to confirm the nutrient levels before making any changes.\n\nIf the plants are struggling, you might want to consider repotting them into fresh soil with better drainage, or even pruning off the yellowed leaves to encourage new growth. Just remember to water them gently and avoid getting water on the leaves directly. If the issue persists, you might want to consult a local garden center for more specific advice.\n\nIf you're still unsure, you could also try a foliar spray of a nitrogen-rich solution, which can sometimes provide a quick boost. However, always test a small section of the plant first to ensure it doesn't react negatively. If the yellowing spreads quickly or the leaves start to drop, it might be a sign of a more serious issue like a pest infestation or disease",
      "source": "target",
